    number: 2,
    title: "The City of Destruction",
    subtitle: "In which Christian flees, and finds he must go alone",
    wordCount: 1050,
    content: `<p>Christian could not rest. He walked the fields in the evenings, sometimes crying out, sometimes falling silent, always weighed down by the Burden he carried. His family watched him with growing alarm. His neighbors began to talk.</p>

<p>One day, while he was walking alone in the fields, he met a man whose name was Evangelist. Evangelist looked at him—really looked at him, the way few people had—and saw exactly what he saw in himself.</p>

<p>"Why are you crying?" Evangelist asked.</p>

<p>"Sir," Christian said, "I understand from this Book in my hand that I am condemned to die, and after that to face judgment. I am not willing to do the first, and I am not able to do the second."</p>

<p>Evangelist listened without dismissing him. Then he asked, "Why are you not willing to die, since life holds so much misery?"</p>

<p>"Because I am afraid that this Burden on my back will sink me lower than the grave. And if I am not fit to go to prison, I am not fit to go to judgment, and from there to execution. These thoughts terrify me."</p>

<p>Evangelist handed him a parchment scroll. On it were written these words: <em>Flee from the wrath to come.</em></p>

<p>"Where must I flee?" Christian asked.</p>

<p>Evangelist pointed across the wide field with his hand. In the far distance, there was a light—small and steady, like a candle set in a window at the end of a long road.</p>

<p>"Do you see that distant wicket gate?" Evangelist asked.</p>

<p>Christian strained to see. "No," he admitted.</p>

<p>"Do you see that shining light?"</p>

<p>He looked again. "I think I do."</p>

<p>"Keep that light in your eye," Evangelist said. "Go directly toward it. When you reach it, you will see the gate. Knock, and you will be told what to do."</p>

<p>Christian turned and ran.</p>

<p>He had not gone far when his wife and children came to the door and called after him. "Come back! Come back!" His wife's voice was strained with something between anger and fear. His children were crying. He covered his ears and ran on, crying himself, shouting, "Life! Life! Eternal life!" He did not look back.</p>

<p>His neighbors watched him go. Two men ran after him—a man named Obstinate, and a man named Pliable. They called to him to return.</p>

<p>Christian stopped and faced them. "No," he said. "You live in the City of Destruction—the same place I was born. I have read that the city is doomed. Dying there, as in the end you must, you will sink below ground into a place worse than the grave. Come with me, and we will find a place that cannot be destroyed."</p>

<p>Obstinate crossed his arms. "What are you leaving behind that you'd make such a fool of yourself to find something better?"</p>

<p>"I am leaving behind everything that can be lost," Christian said. "I am going to find what cannot be taken away. Come with me and you will find that what I am leaving is nothing to what we will gain. Read about it in this Book."</p>

<p>Obstinate looked at the Book with contempt. He had no interest in it. He told Pliable he was going home, and that Christian was clearly mad, and that sensible men didn't throw away a comfortable life on the strength of something written in a book. Then he turned and went back.</p>

<p>Pliable hesitated. The things Christian described—a country whose ruler was love, an eternal inheritance that could not be taken, a life beyond death—they pulled at something in him. He decided he would go.</p>

<p>"I am glad you are coming," Christian said, and they walked on together through the field.</p>

<p>Pliable was full of questions. What was this country like? Who lived there? How did they get in? Christian answered as best he could from what he had read. There were crowns of gold. There were garments that shone like the sun. There would be no more mourning or crying or pain. They would walk with the King forever, and the years of his reign had no end.</p>

<p>Pliable's eyes lit up. "If all this is true," he said, "let's hurry. Let's pick up the pace."</p>

<p>"I would gladly go faster," Christian said, "if only this Burden on my back were not so heavy."</p>

<p>They walked on, talking eagerly, into the field ahead. Neither of them noticed the treacherous ground ahead—the miry bog that lay directly in their path.</p>

<p>Before either of them could stop, they had walked straight into it.</p>`,
