    number: 3,
    title: "The Slough of Despond",
    subtitle: "In which two pilgrims sink, and only one is rescued",
    wordCount: 900,
    content: `<p>The bog was called the Slough of Despond—a wide stretch of soft, swampy ground that had been gathering filth for as long as anyone could remember. It lay directly in the path between the City of Destruction and the Wicket Gate, and many had stumbled into it before them.</p>

<p>Christian sank immediately. The Burden on his back drove him down into the mire. He thrashed and struggled, trying to find solid ground, but every step sank him deeper. Pliable was beside him, also floundering, and the panic of it stripped away whatever determination had brought him this far.</p>

<p>"Is this the happiness you talked about?" Pliable demanded, his voice tight with anger. He fought his way toward the edge—the edge nearest his own house, the side he had come from—and dragged himself out. He was covered in mud and furious. He looked back at Christian once, still struggling in the middle of the mire, and then turned and made his way home.</p>

<p>Christian was alone.</p>

<p>He could not get out. The Burden pressed him down. He reached toward the far side—the side that led toward the light, toward the gate—but his arms found nothing to grip and his feet found no bottom and the mud was in his mouth and his eyes and the despair was as thick as the mire itself.</p>

<p>Then a hand reached in and seized him.</p>

<p>It was Help—a man who had clearly pulled others from this place before, whose hand was certain and strong. He pulled Christian up out of the bog and set him on solid ground on the far side.</p>

<p>"Why did you not look for the stepping stones?" Help asked.</p>

<p>Christian looked back at the Slough and saw them—a line of flat stones just beneath the surface, set there to carry pilgrims safely across. He had been too frightened and desperate to look for them.</p>

<p>"What is this place?" Christian asked. "And why has no one filled it in?"</p>

<p>"This Slough is such a place as cannot be mended," Help said. "It is not the pleasure of the King that this place should remain foul, but it cannot be otherwise. It is the place where the filth and scum of sin continually runs, and therefore it is called the Slough of Despond."</p>

<p>He went on to explain: when a man first wakes up to his sinfulness and starts toward the gate of salvation, fears and doubts rise up in him like mud—guilt over what he has done, uncertainty about whether grace could really cover it, terror at what he faces, grief over what he is leaving behind. All of this collects in the soul like water in a hollow place. No amount of good intentions can keep it dry. The only way through is to find the stepping stones—the promises of God set there by the King himself, carved and placed for exactly this purpose—and to step on those rather than on the shifting ground of feeling.</p>

<p>"But the stones are hard to see in the dark," Help said quietly, "and pilgrims in their fear often miss them."</p>

<p>Christian thanked him. He wrung the mud from his coat and looked ahead toward the gate. His Burden was still there. He was still wet and shaking. But he was on the far side.</p>

<p>He set off again.</p>

<p>Pliable, meanwhile, had made his way back to the city. His neighbors came out to meet him, and those who shared his nature laughed at him—not at his failure to cross, but at his foolishness in ever trying. Having been mocked once for going, he was now mocked for coming back. He crept home ashamed, and for a while he avoided talking about any of it.</p>

<p>The difference between the two was not courage. Pliable's resolve had been built on excitement about the destination—the crowns and the garments and the eternal life—but it had no foundation below it. When the first real difficulty came, there was nothing to stand on. Christian, by contrast, was driven not by excitement but by desperation. He was fleeing something. The wrath behind him was more real to him than the mud around him. And so he reached for the far bank even when he could not see it.</p>

<p>That is often how it is. The pilgrim who keeps going through the Slough is rarely the most enthusiastic one. He is the one who has nowhere else to go.</p>`,
