    wordCount: 1020,
    content: `<p>Christian was still wet from the Slough when he met the man on the road.</p>

<p>The man was well-dressed and confident—the kind of man who always seems to know more than you and is happy to tell you so. His name was Mr. Worldly Wiseman, and he came from the town of Carnal Policy, a large and prosperous town not far from the City of Destruction. He looked Christian up and down—the muddy coat, the Burden, the anxious eyes—and nodded as if he had seen exactly this before.</p>

<p>"Fellow," he said pleasantly, "where are you headed, with that great burden on your back?"</p>

<p>Christian told him: he was going to the Wicket Gate, on the advice of Evangelist. He hoped to find there some relief from the load he carried.</p>

<p>Mr. Worldly Wiseman clicked his tongue sympathetically. "Do you have a wife and children?"</p>

<p>"Yes."</p>

<p>"And you've left them to go on this road?" He shook his head. "I'd hate to see you suffer any more than you already have. Let me give you some advice. That man Evangelist has sent you on the most dangerous path in the world. You will find nothing on it but hardship, hunger, darkness, death, and every kind of misery. The road to the Wicket Gate is no place for a family man."</p>

<p>Christian felt a flicker of doubt. "But this Burden—I cannot live with it. I must find relief."</p>

<p>"I can tell you where to find relief," Mr. Worldly Wiseman said, "and much more safely than by this road. Not far from here is the village of Morality. In that village lives a gentleman named Mr. Legality—a very clever man, very well-regarded, who has skills in lifting such burdens. Many have gone to him and been helped. He even has a son—a fine young man named Civility—who has learned the same trade. Either of them can help you. And once you are free of your Burden, you will also find much easier housing there than you could get in that distant country you've heard of."</p>

<p>Christian hesitated. It was a persuasive picture. Relief from his Burden—and close by, not at the end of a long and dangerous road. A house. Stability. A place to settle his family. All of it sounded entirely reasonable.</p>

<p>"Can you show me the way to Mr. Legality's house?" he asked.</p>

<p>Mr. Worldly Wiseman pointed to a mountain just ahead. "Go past that mountain, and the first house you see will be his."</p>

<p>Christian left the road and went toward the mountain. But as he drew near, the mountain reared up on all sides of him, so steep and heavy that he feared it would fall on him. His Burden pressed harder. Flashes of fire came out of the mountain, and he stood trembling, not daring to go further.</p>

<p>He was frozen there—between the road he had left and the house he could not reach—when he heard a familiar voice behind him.</p>

<p>Evangelist.</p>

<p>"What are you doing here?" Evangelist asked. His voice was grave.</p>

<p>Christian was ashamed. He could hardly look at him. Evangelist asked him to explain himself, and Christian told him everything—about Mr. Worldly Wiseman and his advice, and how it had seemed so reasonable.</p>

<p>Evangelist did not soften his response. He told Christian plainly that he had sinned—that he had listened to a stranger and turned aside from the only road that leads to life. The mountain Christian had approached was Mount Sinai—the mountain of the Law—and it killed anyone who tried to find relief there. Mr. Legality could not help him. The Law cannot save. It was never meant to save. It was meant to show man his condition, not to fix it.</p>

<p>"No man living has ever been rid of his Burden by Mr. Legality," Evangelist said. "No man ever will be. The Law cannot give the righteousness needed to remove guilt. That is the work of the Wicket Gate—and of what lies beyond it."</p>

<p>Christian's eyes filled with tears. He had wasted time. He had turned aside from the way. He feared he was so far gone that there was no return.</p>

<p>"Would the man at the gate receive me now?" he asked.</p>

<p>"The man at the gate has never turned away anyone who came honestly to him," Evangelist said. "Go. And this time, do not let anyone turn you from the road."</p>

<p>Christian thanked him and went back to the road—running this time, saying nothing to anyone he passed, his eyes fixed on the distant light.</p>`,
