    number: 5,
    title: "The Wicket Gate",
    subtitle: "In which Christian knocks, and is let in with urgency",
    wordCount: 880,
    content: `<p>The gate was small—smaller than Christian expected for something with so much weight attached to it. A single narrow door set in a wall, at the top of a path that rose gently through open ground. Above the gate, carved into the stone, were words from the Book: <em>Knock, and the door shall be opened unto you.</em></p>

<p>Christian knocked. Then he knocked again. Then he stood waiting, and the minutes felt long.</p>

<p>Finally he knocked a third time and called out:</p>

<p><em>May I now enter here? Will he within<br>
Open to sorry me, though I have been<br>
An undeserving rebel? Then I will<br>
Not fail to sing his lasting praise on high.</em></p>

<p>A grave and serious man came to the gate. His name was Goodwill.</p>

<p>"Who is there?" Goodwill called from within. "Where do you come from? What do you want?"</p>

<p>"I am a poor burdened sinner. I have come from the City of Destruction. I am going to Mount Zion, that I may be delivered from the wrath to come. I have been told that this is the way. I would like to know, sir, if you are willing to let me in."</p>

<p>The door swung open. And then something happened that Christian had not expected: Goodwill seized him by the arm and pulled him through quickly, with force, stepping aside immediately afterward and shutting the door behind them.</p>

<p>Christian stood inside, blinking. "Why did you pull me in so fast?"</p>

<p>Goodwill pointed back through a narrow window in the wall. Not far from the gate, on a strong fortification belonging to Beelzebub, stood archers. They shot arrows at any who came to the gate—trying to kill pilgrims before they could enter. Several had fallen there. It was always best to come boldly and enter quickly.</p>

<p>Christian looked back and shuddered. He thought of the hesitation on the road, the time he had wasted with Mr. Worldly Wiseman. He might have turned aside permanently. He might have been shot while loitering. The grace that had brought him to this gate was more urgent, and more contested, than he had known.</p>

<p>"Are you alone?" Goodwill asked.</p>

<p>Christian told him about his wife and children—that he had asked them to come and they had refused. About Pliable, who had come partway and turned back at the Slough. About the trouble with Mr. Worldly Wiseman and Mr. Legality and the mountain. He told it all, with his face downward, because he was ashamed of how much of it had gone wrong.</p>

<p>Goodwill was not harsh with him. "Your sins and failures brought you to this gate," he said quietly. "But none of that is why you are here. You are here because the door was always open for you. Come in—you are welcome."</p>

<p>He showed Christian the narrow path that stretched ahead through the gate, wide enough for one, running straight. "This is the way you must walk," Goodwill said. "It was laid out by the Patriarchs and Prophets and by Christ himself. It is as straight as a ruler can make it. There are crooked paths that branch off from it on either side, but the right way is only one, and it is straight."</p>

<p>Christian noticed something. "Is my Burden never to be lifted?" The weight was still there, pressing down on him, even in the relief of being inside the gate.</p>

<p>"Bear it a little further," Goodwill said. "When you come to the Place of Deliverance, it will fall from your back by itself."</p>

<p>Christian thanked him and set off down the narrow path.</p>

<p>Before he had gone far, Goodwill called after him: "A little way from here is the house of the Interpreter. Knock at his door, and he will show you excellent things—things that will help you for the journey."</p>

<p>Christian nodded and walked on. The path before him was narrow and straight. The gate was behind him now, shut. And whatever else lay ahead, this at least was certain: he was inside.</p>`,
